 Police found the baby wrapped in a blanket, with an extra diaper and full milk bottle. In the letter, written in English and Siswati, the woman asks the SAPS not to try and trace her because she cannot care for her child as a sex worker.
She pleads with social workers to find the baby a loving family that will adopt the child. “As a sex worker, I do not know who the father of the child is. Just make sure you find good parents for him,” it reads.
She also included the baby’s name and date of birth. Police took the baby to social workers. • In July, Mhluzi Police found a newborn baby in a toilet in Extension 4, but the mother was nowhere to be found. • In June last year, a woman found a baby in a refuse bin in Joubert Street. This specific incident prompted Francis Davis to start the Precious Life Baby Project, resulting in the first baby safe being constructed at St John’s Presbyterian Church.  Hawks members sent to jail for fraud WATCH: The Place of Refuge – Once a vibrant village, now a ghost town WATCH: Robbery caught on video, police looking for suspects Three counts of poaching in one week – and the toll keeps rising   • Save our standby number (072 248 3855) and send us a WhatsApp message with the words “Add me” to be added to our broadcast list. • Like us on Facebook, follow us on Twitter and Instagram. • Subscribe to our YouTube channel. • Click on the link to subscribe to our bi-weekly newsletter via email. Contact our news room on our 24 hr standby number 072 248 3855, or send a mail to our editor tobie@mobserver.co.za